  "source_text_quote": "Discontent with colonial rule began shortly after the defeat of France in the French and Indian War in 1763. Even though the colonies had fought in and supported the war, British Parliament imposed new taxes to compensate for wartime costs..."
}

{
  "probative_value": 0.8,
  "certainty": 0.9,
  "source_text_quote": "...and turned control of the colonies' western lands over to the British officials in Montreal."
}

{
  "probative_value": 0.7,
  "certainty": 0.8,
  "source_text_quote": "In early 1763, the Bute ministry decided to permanently garrison 10,000 soldiers in North America."
}

{
  "constraint_strength": 0.7,
  "constraint_type": "channels",
  "certainty": 0.8,
  "source_text_quote": "This would allow approximately 1,500 politically well-connected British Army officers to remain on active duty with full pay (stationing a standing army in Great Britain during peacetime was politically unacceptable)."
}

{
  "necessity": 0.7,
  "enabling_type": "structural",
  "certainty": 0.8,
  "source_text_quote": "Stationing troops in North America on a permanent basis would cost another \u00a3360,000 a year. ... Grenville believed that the colonies should help pay the troop costs."
}

{
  "probative_value": 0.8,
  "certainty": 0.9,
  "source_text_quote": "Migration beyond the Appalachian Mountains increased after the French threat was removed, and Native Americans launched Pontiac's War (1763\u20131766) in response."
